  "text": "ER proteostasis regulators selectively reduce secretion of amyloidogenic TTR from liver-derived HepG2 cells ER reprogramming afforded by stress-independent chemical genetic ATF6 activation selectively reduces secretion of destabilized, amyloidogenic TTR variants from liver-derived HepG2 cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Thus, small molecule ER proteostasis regulators that preferentially activate the ATF6 transcriptional program, such as 147 and 263, should similarly reduce secretion of destabilized, amyloidogenic TTR from HepG2 cells. We confirmed that 147 and 263 induced expression of the ATF6-target gene BiP in HepG2 cells by qPCR ( Figure 5-figure supplement 1A) . We also showed that the treatment dose of these small molecules (10 mM) does not influence HepG2 viability, although higher concentrations (100 mM) do reduce viability ( Figure 5-figure supplement 1B) .",
